  "prompt": "Why are liquids not allowed on flights?",
  "response": "The restriction on carrying liquids on flights primarily stems from security concerns. In 2006, security agencies foiled a terrorist plot in the UK where attackers planned to use liquid explosives to detonate bombs on transatlantic flights. Subsequently, aviation authorities around the world implemented strict rules to mitigate the risk of explosives being smuggled onboard using liquid substances.\n\nThese regulations typically limit the amount of liquid each passenger can carry in their hand luggage. In many places, this means liquids must be in containers no larger than 100 milliliters (about 3.4 ounces) and all containers must fit within a single, transparent, resealable plastic bag, often with a total volume limit of about one liter (approximately one quart). Exceptions are generally made for essential liquids such as medications and baby formula.\n\nThese rules were established to ensure the safety of passengers by making it more difficult for potential threats to bring harmful substances on board aircraft.",
